            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What this date calculator can do</h2>
              <p>
                This multi-purpose date calculator combines the most common date
                and time tasks in one place:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Add or subtract calendar days, weeks, months, or years from
                  any date.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Move forward or backward by business days only (skip
                  weekends).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Find the number of days between two dates, with optional
                  inclusive counting.
                </li>
                <li>
                  See how many weekdays and weekend days fall in a date range.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Calculate age in years, months, and days, plus total days and
                  months lived.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How date addition and subtraction works</h2>
              <p>
                When you add or subtract a period from a date, the calculator
                applies the components in a clear order:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Add or subtract years.</li>
                <li>Add or subtract months.</li>
                <li>Convert weeks to days and add to days.</li>
                <li>Apply the resulting number of days.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                For calendar calculations, months and years are applied using
                the Gregorian calendar. If the target month doesn’t have the
                same day (for example, adding 1 month to January 31), the date
                is clamped to the last valid day of the month (February 28 or
                29, April 30, etc.).
              </p>

              <h3>Business day (weekday) addition</h3>
              <p>
                When you choose <strong>Workdays only</strong>, the calculator:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Starts from the base date.</li>
                <li>Moves forward (or backward) one day at a time.</li>
                <li>Counts only Monday through Friday as business days.</li>
                <li>Skips Saturdays and Sundays.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Public holidays are not excluded automatically, because they
                vary by country and region. If you need to account for holidays,
                subtract them manually from the result.
              </p>

              <h2>Days between dates: formulas and logic</h2>
              <p>Conceptually, the number of days between two dates is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>days = |date<sub>2</sub> − date<sub>1</sub>|</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you choose to <strong>include the end date</strong>, the
                calculator adds 1 to this difference.
              </p>
              <p>
                To count weekdays and weekend days, the tool iterates through
                the range and classifies each day by its weekday number (0 =
                Sunday, 1 = Monday, …, 6 = Saturday).
              </p>

              <h2>How age is calculated</h2>
              <p>Age in years, months, and days is computed in three steps:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Count full years between birth date and reference date.</li>
                <li>
                  From that anniversary, count full months until the next month
                  would exceed the reference date.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The remaining difference in days is the final component.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                This approach matches how age is typically expressed and
                correctly handles different month lengths and leap years.
              </p>

              <h2>Common use cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Find a project deadline a certain number of business days from
                  today.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Calculate how many days remain until a due date or event.
                </li>
                <li>Work out the exact age of a person, pet, or contract.</li>
                <li>
                  Measure the duration of a rental, subscription, or warranty
                  period.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  All calculations use the proleptic Gregorian calendar as
                  implemented by your browser.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Time zones are not considered; dates are treated as local
                  dates without times.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Business day calculations skip weekends but not public
                  holidays.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-10" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Date calculator FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does this calculator handle leap years correctly?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. The underlying date engine follows the Gregorian leap
                    year rules (years divisible by 4, except centuries not
                    divisible by 400). February 29 in leap years is treated as a
                    valid date and is included in day counts and age
                    calculations.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the difference between inclusive and exclusive day
                    counts?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    An exclusive count measures the difference between two dates
                    (end minus start). An inclusive count adds 1 day so that
                    both the start and end dates are counted. For example, from
                    January 1 to January 1 is 0 days exclusive, but 1 day
                    inclusive.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use this as a workday or business day calculator?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
